1
00:00:06,126 --> 00:00:08,671
["OLD MOTHER HUBBARD"
BY ELLA FITZGERALD PLAYING]

2
00:00:10,673 --> 00:00:13,133
-That's sold.
-It is? We just got here.

3
00:00:13,217 --> 00:00:14,801
Most of the pieces here are already sold.

4
00:00:14,885 --> 00:00:16,220
Isn't this the opening?

5
00:00:16,304 --> 00:00:18,306
They invite serious collectors
to come to the pre-opening.

6
00:00:18,390 --> 00:00:20,308
-I bought those three last week.
-How much?

7
00:00:20,392 --> 00:00:21,517
-For this one?
-Yeah.

8
00:00:21,601 --> 00:00:22,810
-$1,200.
-You're kidding.

9
00:00:22,894 --> 00:00:24,479
I got to get Ethan a paint set.

10
00:00:24,563 --> 00:00:26,939
Oh, Parsons. Ha!
It's Parsons. That's Parsons.

11
00:00:27,023 --> 00:00:30,026
I have to go talk to him.

12
00:00:30,110 --> 00:00:32,069
-I'm coming back.
-Oh.

13
00:00:32,153 --> 00:00:33,821
<i>♪ And he barked, whoo, whoo ♪</i>

14
00:00:33,905 --> 00:00:35,615
<i>♪ Looked Hubbard straight in the eye… ♪</i>

15
00:00:35,699 --> 00:00:37,158
What do you feel?

16
00:00:37,242 --> 00:00:38,785
Hungry. I thought there'd be snacks.

17
00:00:38,869 --> 00:00:41,662
-You just seemed very immersed.
-In what?

18
00:00:41,746 --> 00:00:43,539
Oh. This, yes. Very.

19
00:00:43,623 --> 00:00:45,584
He paints completely naked.

20
00:00:45,668 --> 00:00:49,797
Well, oil-based paint is really
hard to get out of most fabrics.

21
00:00:49,881 --> 00:00:52,007
Seriously, how do you
respond to, "He paints naked"?

22
00:00:52,091 --> 00:00:54,051
I'm just asking.

23
00:00:54,135 --> 00:00:55,803
-How was Parsons?
-Very angry.

24
00:00:55,887 --> 00:00:57,721
I bought those paintings
right out from under him.

25
00:00:57,805 --> 00:00:59,473
-And this makes you happy?
-Extremely.

26
00:00:59,557 --> 00:01:01,183
He stole a Rauschenberg
from me last month.

27
00:01:01,267 --> 00:01:03,268
Bastard waited till I
was ordering a drink.

28
00:01:03,352 --> 00:01:05,103
Bam. Flew in, cash on the table.

29
00:01:05,187 --> 00:01:07,105
Plus, the bartender got my drink wrong.

30
00:01:07,189 --> 00:01:09,942
So how are you? Good? Yes?
Having fun? It's fun, right?

31
00:01:10,026 --> 00:01:12,528
Little question: Have you
been popping mama's diet pills?

32
00:01:12,612 --> 00:01:15,031
I get a little excited when it
comes to art and revenge.

33
00:01:15,115 --> 00:01:17,200
-Sure.
-This is a particularly great show.

34
00:01:17,284 --> 00:01:19,077
Solomon Crespi has been
around for a few years,

35
00:01:19,161 --> 00:01:20,745
but this show, this could
be his breakthrough.

36
00:01:20,829 --> 00:01:23,039
And I got three of his
paintings and Parsons got none.

37
00:01:23,123 --> 00:01:24,916
-Ah! David Mellman. David!
-Do you hate him, too?

38
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:26,042
Should we take him out?

39
00:01:26,126 --> 00:01:27,961
You buy his art while
I go fuck up his drink?

40
00:01:28,045 --> 00:01:30,255
-Where the hell have you been all my life?
-Riverside Drive and 113th.

41
00:01:30,339 --> 00:01:32,757
-I just needed to take a walk in the park.
-Live and learn.

42
00:01:32,841 --> 00:01:34,634
You are a great date
to bring to something

43
00:01:34,718 --> 00:01:36,511
you know nothing about
and have no interest in.

44
00:01:36,595 --> 00:01:38,388
Wait till you see me at a boxing match.

45
00:01:38,472 --> 00:01:39,639
I'm gonna get you another drink.

46
00:01:39,723 --> 00:01:40,807
You're going to gloat.

47
00:01:40,891 --> 00:01:42,475
But I'm going to gloat by the bar,

48
00:01:42,559 --> 00:01:44,727
-so two birds, one stone.
-Martini, two olives.

49
00:01:44,811 --> 00:01:47,147
-Cold, it's cold.
-It's the coldness I crave.

50
00:01:47,231 --> 00:01:48,816
The coldness is brilliant.

51
00:01:48,900 --> 00:01:51,735
It's the coldness that gets
you hung in the Whitney.

52
00:01:51,819 --> 00:01:54,488
<i>♪ Mother Hubbard, bring me some meat ♪</i>

53
00:01:54,572 --> 00:01:58,242
<i>♪ Pork chops, chicken, fish bone ♪</i>

54
00:01:58,326 --> 00:02:01,370
<i>♪ Anything you see ♪</i>

55
00:02:01,454 --> 00:02:04,665
<i>♪ Somewhere, somewhere
in this wide, wide world ♪</i>

56
00:02:04,749 --> 00:02:07,585
<i>♪ There must be a bone for me ♪</i>

57
00:02:07,669 --> 00:02:11,422
<i>♪ Doggone, said the little dog ♪</i>

58
00:02:11,506 --> 00:02:13,841
<i>♪ That ain't the way to do ♪</i>

59
00:02:13,925 --> 00:02:15,468
<i>♪ If you were hungry… ♪</i>

60
00:02:15,552 --> 00:02:17,971
-Excuse me. Is this sold?
-No.

61
00:02:18,055 --> 00:02:20,390
Don't you want to see
which one I'm pointing to?

62
00:02:20,474 --> 00:02:22,324
It's not sold. None of them are sold.

63
00:02:24,395 --> 00:02:26,689
-How much?
-Twenty-five bucks.

64
00:02:31,527 --> 00:02:33,653
Do I just… take it off the wall?

65
00:02:33,737 --> 00:02:35,155
It can't follow you home.

66
00:02:35,239 --> 00:02:37,908
<i>♪ Said the little dog ♪</i>

67
00:02:37,992 --> 00:02:41,620
<i>♪ That ain't the way to do… ♪</i>

68
00:02:41,704 --> 00:02:45,374
-Hey. Look what I got.
-Where'd you find that?

69
00:02:45,458 --> 00:02:47,209
There's this sad little room back there.

70
00:02:47,293 --> 00:02:49,295
Oh, yeah, that's where they
put the very minor artists,

71
00:02:49,379 --> 00:02:50,713
or the mops.

72
00:02:50,797 --> 00:02:53,341
Well, I didn't see a mop,
just paintings, like this.

73
00:02:53,425 --> 00:02:57,428
-Oh, hey, it came with a hat.
-All the great ones do.

74
00:02:57,512 --> 00:02:59,680
I like it. My first art acquisition.

75
00:02:59,764 --> 00:03:01,349
I hope you haggled the price down.

76
00:03:01,433 --> 00:03:03,184
-Nope, paid full price.
-Which was?

77
00:03:03,268 --> 00:03:04,852
-Twenty-five bucks.
-You overpaid.

78
00:03:04,936 --> 00:03:07,396
-But… hat.
-Right.

79
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:09,774
Okay. I'm done here.

80
00:03:09,858 --> 00:03:12,568
I've circled, I've gloated.
Where do you want to go?

81
00:03:12,652 --> 00:03:13,986
It's your night.

82
00:03:14,070 --> 00:03:15,656
There's a little gathering
at the Cedar Tavern.

83
00:03:15,740 --> 00:03:17,074
It's a place artists hang out.

84
00:03:17,158 --> 00:03:19,201
I've never been, but I've
heard you should never go in

85
00:03:19,285 --> 00:03:20,577
wearing light-colored clothing.

86
00:03:20,661 --> 00:03:22,871
Ooh, a dirty bar, my favorite kind.

87
00:03:22,955 --> 00:03:25,457
Let's go.

88
00:03:25,541 --> 00:03:28,126
Nice ladder.

89
00:03:28,210 --> 00:03:31,254
<i>♪ Mother Huzzard, bring me that muzzard ♪</i>

90
00:03:31,338 --> 00:03:33,966
♪♪

91
00:03:34,050 --> 00:03:35,592
This is the midnight blue velvet;

92
00:03:35,676 --> 00:03:37,928
this is the ocean blue velveteen.

93
00:03:38,012 --> 00:03:40,097
Clear? Yes? Good. Cut.

94
00:03:40,181 --> 00:03:41,974
I got a case of
champagne here for Maisel.

95
00:03:42,058 --> 00:03:43,266
I got it.

96
00:03:43,350 --> 00:03:44,936
Manny, what was the
deal with the cigarettes?

97
00:03:45,020 --> 00:03:47,230
-One for you, one for me.
-And how many is that?

98
00:03:47,314 --> 00:03:48,439
Five.

99
00:03:48,523 --> 00:03:50,483
So you see where the dealmaking
process went awry here?

100
00:03:50,567 --> 00:03:51,943
-All right, all right.
-Put it out.

101
00:03:52,027 --> 00:03:53,695
-As soon as I'm done.
-Now.

102
00:03:53,779 --> 00:03:56,781
-Two more puffs?
-Master negotiator.

103
00:03:56,865 --> 00:04:00,284
Mrs. Moskowitz, I want a
glass in everybody's hands.

104
00:04:00,368 --> 00:04:02,412
Put out the fucking cigarette, Manny.

105
00:04:02,496 --> 00:04:04,038
I got more booze.

106
00:04:04,122 --> 00:04:06,332
Exactly what we need in
a room full of giant scissors

107
00:04:06,416 --> 00:04:07,750
and sharp electric implements.

108
00:04:07,834 --> 00:04:09,377
Joel, are we still on for tonight?

109
00:04:09,461 --> 00:04:12,672
-Absolutely, 10:00.
-Swell. Got to go find my pants.

110
00:04:12,756 --> 00:04:14,967
-Does she, though?
-Hand out those glasses.

111
00:04:15,051 --> 00:04:17,886
Everyone, stop working.
Turn off your machines and gather round.

112
00:04:17,970 --> 00:04:19,722
MOSKOWITZ: Mr. Maisel, one question.

113
00:04:19,806 --> 00:04:21,682
-Is this an official meeting?
-Is what an official meeting?

114
00:04:21,766 --> 00:04:23,892
The ten o'clock rendezvous with
the young lady without the pants.

115
00:04:23,976 --> 00:04:25,519
-No.
-Because if it's official,

116
00:04:25,603 --> 00:04:27,354
I should put it on
your official itinerary.

117
00:04:27,438 --> 00:04:29,148
The champagne, Mrs. Moskowitz.

118
00:04:29,232 --> 00:04:30,649
Come on, everyone.

119
00:04:30,733 --> 00:04:33,402
I promise this won't affect your hours.

120
00:04:35,404 --> 00:04:37,740
Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls,

121
00:04:37,824 --> 00:04:39,825
-I have an announcement to make.
-[SHUSHING]

122
00:04:39,909 --> 00:04:42,536
At 4:00 this afternoon, I
went down to the bank,

123
00:04:42,620 --> 00:04:45,957
and after some
negotiating, some pleading,

124
00:04:46,041 --> 00:04:47,709
some bloodletting, this building,

125
00:04:47,793 --> 00:04:50,170
the building that houses the
Maisel and Roth Garment Company,

126
00:04:50,254 --> 00:04:51,755
-is officially ours.
-[EXCITED MURMURING]

127
00:04:51,839 --> 00:04:54,799
We bought it, we own
it, it will absolutely kill us,

128
00:04:54,883 --> 00:04:56,426
the interest is criminal,

129
00:04:56,510 --> 00:04:58,553
I anticipate dropping
dead right on this spot,

130
00:04:58,637 --> 00:05:00,513
but I own this spot, I get to.

131
00:05:00,597 --> 00:05:02,307
[LAUGHTER]

132
00:05:02,391 --> 00:05:04,851
Such a strange mixture
of happiness and horror.

133
00:05:04,935 --> 00:05:06,644
Oh, you're clearly not Jewish, dear.

134
00:05:06,728 --> 00:05:08,980
I'd also like to toast my friend Archie,

135
00:05:09,064 --> 00:05:11,191
who's expecting baby
number three any day now.

136
00:05:11,275 --> 00:05:13,234
-It's gonna be so loud.
-[LAUGHTER]

137
00:05:13,318 --> 00:05:15,821
And to Mrs. Moskowitz,
who left Tri-Borough Plastics

138
00:05:15,905 --> 00:05:17,239
to join me here full-time.

139
00:05:17,323 --> 00:05:19,617
You are saving my life, Mrs. Moskowitz.

140
00:05:19,701 --> 00:05:22,745
Yeah. Say a few words, Mrs. Moskowitz.

141
00:05:22,829 --> 00:05:26,332
Thank you. Could everyone
please use a coaster for your drinks?

142
00:05:26,416 --> 00:05:28,209
Hell of a speech, Mrs. Moskowitz.

143
00:05:28,293 --> 00:05:30,544
-[LAUGHTER, CLAPPING]
-Enjoy the food and the drinks,

144
00:05:30,628 --> 00:05:33,380
because you people
are the Roth to my Maisel,

145
00:05:33,464 --> 00:05:35,466
and I thank you very much.

146
00:05:38,970 --> 00:05:41,263
♪♪

147
00:05:41,347 --> 00:05:43,390
Congratulations, Joel.

148
00:05:43,474 --> 00:05:45,310
-Thank you…
-[MOUTHING]

149
00:05:45,394 --> 00:05:47,395
-Velma.
-Are we still on for tonight?

150
00:05:47,479 --> 00:05:48,522
-Yes.
-No.

151
00:05:48,606 --> 00:05:50,440
No, not tonight. Sunday could work.

152
00:05:50,524 --> 00:05:52,859
-Yom Kippur.
-Sunday's not good. Tuesday?

153
00:05:52,943 --> 00:05:54,611
-Tuesday is good.
-Tuesday is good.

154
00:05:54,695 --> 00:05:56,947
Okay. [CHUCKLES] Thanks.

155
00:05:57,031 --> 00:05:59,157
You got quite a harem going there.

156
00:05:59,241 --> 00:06:01,868
-Looking for a new wife?
-No. No wives.

157
00:06:01,952 --> 00:06:04,621
I had a wife. I've done wives.
I'm just dating.

158
00:06:04,705 --> 00:06:06,498
You have to leave the apartment to date.

159
00:06:06,582 --> 00:06:08,416
He doesn't leave the
apartment or buy them dinner.

160
00:06:08,500 --> 00:06:10,418
Hey, what's with the
teaming up on the guy

161
00:06:10,502 --> 00:06:11,711
who sprung for the champagne?

162
00:06:11,795 --> 00:06:13,004
We're just concerned about you.

163
00:06:13,088 --> 00:06:14,757
Don't want you to get a bad reputation.

164
00:06:14,841 --> 00:06:15,444
Couple of girls.

165
00:06:15,528 --> 00:06:17,426
Joel, can we do Thursday
instead of Wednesday?

166
00:06:17,510 --> 00:06:19,303
I'm gonna have to take
my mother to church.

167
00:06:19,387 --> 00:06:21,264
Thursday's fine.

168
00:06:21,348 --> 00:06:24,308
What? It is.

169
00:06:24,392 --> 00:06:26,519
We don't expect you to be alone.

170
00:06:26,603 --> 00:06:28,938
We'd just like you to not
pick up a venereal disease.

171
00:06:29,022 --> 00:06:30,356
I appreciate that.

172
00:06:30,440 --> 00:06:32,191
What are you doing for Yom Kippur?

173
00:06:32,275 --> 00:06:34,735
You're welcome to break fast
with me and my sister in Queens.

174
00:06:34,819 --> 00:06:36,779
She makes a brisket with Coca-Cola.

175
00:06:36,863 --> 00:06:40,283
Sounds terrific, Mrs. Moskowitz,
but I'm going to the Weissmans.

176
00:06:40,367 --> 00:06:43,244
Very civilized. Dinner with the ex.

177
00:06:43,328 --> 00:06:45,581
Ethan asked me to come, so I'm coming.

178
00:06:45,665 --> 00:06:48,375
You know, it was exactly one year ago

179
00:06:48,459 --> 00:06:50,586
I blew up my entire life.

180
00:06:52,588 --> 00:06:55,465
Yom Kippur, atone for your sins.

181
00:06:55,549 --> 00:06:58,052
I'm the fucking poster boy.

182
00:07:00,054 --> 00:07:04,975
Well, if you're gonna do the
crime, you got to do the time.

183
00:07:05,059 --> 00:07:09,105
I'm gonna make the rounds.
Drink up. It's a celebration.

184
00:07:11,357 --> 00:07:14,234
-[MUSIC PLAYING, LIVELY CHATTER]
-This place is a zoo.

185
00:07:14,318 --> 00:07:16,446
You go to a surgeon's
bar, it's nothing like this.

186
00:07:16,530 --> 00:07:18,865
-Hmm.
-Wow, wow, w… wow.

187
00:07:18,949 --> 00:07:21,534
-Add a word, any word.
-That's Franz Kline.

188
00:07:21,618 --> 00:07:23,161
-It is?
-Do you know him?

189
00:07:23,245 --> 00:07:25,121
-No.
-Oh, I do. I own him.

190
00:07:25,205 --> 00:07:26,497
How colonial of you.

191
00:07:26,581 --> 00:07:28,875
No, I mean a painting.
It's hanging in my living room.

192
00:07:28,959 --> 00:07:31,878
It's tiny, but it's Franz Kline. Wow.

193
00:07:31,962 --> 00:07:33,922
Robert Motherwell. Holy…
That's Robert Motherwell.

194
00:07:34,006 --> 00:07:35,632
-Robert Motherwell!
-You know him?

195
00:07:35,716 --> 00:07:38,218
-Didn't we just do this?
-Right. I'm sorry.

196
00:07:38,302 --> 00:07:39,636
I just… He's in my hall.

197
00:07:39,720 --> 00:07:41,429
Yikes. Franz Kline got the living room.

198
00:07:41,513 --> 00:07:43,556
It's a great hall. There's a bench.

199
00:07:43,640 --> 00:07:45,559
-John Lambert.
-Thank God you're Jewish.

200
00:07:45,643 --> 00:07:47,811
Christmas morning would kill you.

201
00:07:47,895 --> 00:07:49,855
Ooh, my turn.

202
00:07:49,939 --> 00:07:53,150
-Jane Jacobs, remember me?
-No.

203
00:07:53,234 --> 00:07:54,860
Washington Square Park.
You were protesting.

204
00:07:54,944 --> 00:07:58,822
I got up and, "Women
will fix it and accessorize it!"

205
00:07:58,906 --> 00:08:01,116
Upper West Side.
How you doing, West Side?

206
00:08:01,200 --> 00:08:03,661
I'm good. I'm on a date with a doctor.

207
00:08:03,745 --> 00:08:05,537
You should come rally
the troops with me again.

208
00:08:05,621 --> 00:08:09,124
I'll be there.

209
00:08:09,208 --> 00:08:11,001
That girl's nuts.

210
00:08:11,085 --> 00:08:12,670
I'm so glad we came here tonight.

211
00:08:12,754 --> 00:08:14,422
So you could stare at Franz Kline?

212
00:08:14,506 --> 00:08:16,299
Yes, and you.

213
00:08:16,383 --> 00:08:18,802
-But mostly Franz Kline.
-Come here.

214
00:08:18,886 --> 00:08:20,929
DECLAN [SLURRING]: Fuck Burroughs!

215
00:08:21,013 --> 00:08:22,597
Fuck all writers!

216
00:08:22,681 --> 00:08:25,725
I'm… I'm… I'm done with writers.

217
00:08:25,809 --> 00:08:28,144
Oh, you're kidding.
That is Declan Howell.

218
00:08:28,228 --> 00:08:30,313
-Declan Howell?
-I'm not falling for that again.

219
00:08:30,397 --> 00:08:33,191
…Shore and Proust and Shakespeare.

220
00:08:33,275 --> 00:08:37,445
God! William Shakespeare
with his, with his "thees"

221
00:08:37,529 --> 00:08:41,157
and "thous" and fairies and Puck.
Fuck Puck!

222
00:08:41,241 --> 00:08:43,493
Declan Howell is the most
famous unknown artist in the world.

223
00:08:43,577 --> 00:08:45,496
He's considered one of
the greats by his peers,

224
00:08:45,580 --> 00:08:46,914
but he can't sell his art.

225
00:08:46,998 --> 00:08:48,624
Well, won't sell his art, actually.

226
00:08:48,708 --> 00:08:50,918
-Why?
-He's crazy. Just won't do it.

227
00:08:51,002 --> 00:08:53,004
And if someone ever
does talk him into a sale,

228
00:08:53,088 --> 00:08:55,047
he always finds a way to get out of it.

229
00:08:55,131 --> 00:08:57,133
Early in his career, he
made a very big sale.

230
00:08:57,217 --> 00:08:59,677
Peggy Guggenheim.
The day she came to pick it up,

231
00:08:59,761 --> 00:09:02,096
he sets it on fire right in front of her,

232
00:09:02,180 --> 00:09:04,432
and then puts the fire out by…

233
00:09:04,516 --> 00:09:06,350
Well, let's just say he did
not use a fire extinguisher.

234
00:09:06,434 --> 00:09:08,477
That's not true.

235
00:09:08,561 --> 00:09:09,979
DECLAN: The last thing I read

236
00:09:10,063 --> 00:09:14,651
that made any sense
to me at all: <i>Peanuts.</i>

237
00:09:14,735 --> 00:09:16,278
There's a story, urban myth maybe,

238
00:09:16,362 --> 00:09:17,612
about a painting he painted.

239
00:09:17,696 --> 00:09:19,072
