981
00:41:13,591 --> 00:41:15,593
[SPEAKING POLISH]

982
00:41:18,262 --> 00:41:20,264
[WOMEN CONVERSING IN POLISH]

983
00:41:23,059 --> 00:41:25,269
Soak the beans at the end.
[SPEAKS POLISH]

984
00:41:25,353 --> 00:41:26,812
You do not know American beans?

985
00:41:26,896 --> 00:41:29,273
-Smells delicious, Zelda.
-Thank you, Miss Miriam.

986
00:41:29,357 --> 00:41:31,984
-At the end, the end, the end!
-I put baby down.

987
00:41:32,068 --> 00:41:34,611
[WOMEN CONTINUE CHATTERING]

988
00:41:34,695 --> 00:41:36,530
SHIRLEY: These latkes are delicious.

989
00:41:36,614 --> 00:41:39,616
-You changed your dress.
-Ethan got chocolate on it.

990
00:41:39,700 --> 00:41:40,951
-Here you go, Pop.
-Just put it down.

991
00:41:41,035 --> 00:41:42,245
It's gonna get warm.

992
00:41:42,329 --> 00:41:44,331
Do you control the temperature now?

993
00:41:44,415 --> 00:41:46,333
No, I ju… forget it.

994
00:41:46,417 --> 00:41:48,626
Drink it, don't drink it.

995
00:41:48,710 --> 00:41:51,838
Thank you for laying
out my options so clearly.

996
00:41:51,922 --> 00:41:53,631
-You look nice.
-Yeah?

997
00:41:53,715 --> 00:41:56,051
-Do I? Thanks.
-You okay?

998
00:41:56,135 --> 00:41:59,304
-Yes. Hungry.
-You sure that's it?

999
00:41:59,388 --> 00:42:04,267
<i>♪ Seem to vanish like a
gambler's lucky streak… ♪</i>

1000
00:42:04,351 --> 00:42:06,770
-Really?
-Where are they going?

1001
00:42:06,854 --> 00:42:09,272
These gatherings just
keep getting weirder.

1002
00:42:09,356 --> 00:42:11,859
-Start over.
-[GROANS]

1003
00:42:11,943 --> 00:42:13,945
[WOMEN CONTINUE CHATTERING]

1004
00:42:17,198 --> 00:42:19,116
I'm going to tell them
about the stand-up.

1005
00:42:19,200 --> 00:42:20,951
-Tonight?
-Tonight.

1006
00:42:21,035 --> 00:42:23,120
Yeah, I don't know if that's
one of your better ideas.

1007
00:42:23,204 --> 00:42:24,955
It isn't mine, it's Papa's.
He's insisting.

1008
00:42:25,039 --> 00:42:27,166
You have a room full
of unfed Jews in there.

1009
00:42:27,250 --> 00:42:29,210
That's a lot of desperation
and rage in the air.

1010
00:42:29,294 --> 00:42:29,543
I know.

1011
00:42:29,627 --> 00:42:31,670
Right now, they'd kill
each other for a garnish.

1012
00:42:31,754 --> 00:42:34,048
I have a gig tonight.
I have to get out of here.

1013
00:42:34,132 --> 00:42:35,841
-He won't cover.
-Maybe I can help.

1014
00:42:35,925 --> 00:42:38,677
Create a diversion.
I can have a stroke. I'm 30.

1015
00:42:38,761 --> 00:42:41,430
In the Maisel family, I should've
had one by now anyhow.

1016
00:42:41,514 --> 00:42:45,227
-[WOMEN CHATTERING]
-[DISHES CLINKING]

1017
00:42:45,311 --> 00:42:48,438
-Happy New Year.
-Happy New Year.

1018
00:42:48,522 --> 00:42:50,857
That's Ethan's cereal.

1019
00:42:50,941 --> 00:42:53,693
Yeah? It's good. Not as good
as the candy bar in temple, but…

1020
00:42:53,777 --> 00:42:56,405
Just make sure that fucking
toy surprise is still in there.

1021
00:42:56,489 --> 00:42:58,949
Look how he talks to his
father on the holiest of days.

1022
00:42:59,033 --> 00:42:59,492
You heard me.

1023
00:42:59,576 --> 00:43:01,284
ZELDA: Two spoonfuls
of dressing per plate.

1024
00:43:01,368 --> 00:43:03,578
Except Mrs. Weissman,
who doesn't eat dressing.

1025
00:43:03,662 --> 00:43:05,205
Anyone who puts dressing

1026
00:43:05,289 --> 00:43:08,583
on Mrs. Weissman's
plate will answer to me.

1027
00:43:08,667 --> 00:43:11,545
Okay, let's go. Dinner is ready!

1028
00:43:11,629 --> 00:43:13,714
-MIDGE: Wait, Zelda.
-Did she say dinner's ready?

1029
00:43:13,798 --> 00:43:16,217
It's ready? It's ready.
Everyone to the table.

1030
00:43:16,301 --> 00:43:18,219
ABE: If I eat one more
onion, I'm gonna throw up.

1031
00:43:18,303 --> 00:43:20,012
I have to climb over the stool?
This is so stressful.

1032
00:43:20,096 --> 00:43:21,806
-Just keep moving.
-Oh.

1033
00:43:21,890 --> 00:43:23,516
Uh, Pop, you left your drink.

1034
00:43:23,600 --> 00:43:26,102
[GROANS] Just worry about
yourself like you always do.

1035
00:43:26,186 --> 00:43:28,521
-Are the salt shakers on the table?
-Hey, a decoder ring!

1036
00:43:28,605 --> 00:43:30,648
-You put that back.
-Fuck if I will.

1037
00:43:30,732 --> 00:43:33,276
-Mama, you dropped a shoe.
-What? Did I?

1038
00:43:33,360 --> 00:43:34,986
I'm not sitting next to you tonight.

1039
00:43:35,070 --> 00:43:36,821
-Oh, lucky me.
-ETHAN: I'm not hungry.

1040
00:43:36,905 --> 00:43:39,449
-Shh.
-What you mean, you're not hungry?

1041
00:43:39,533 --> 00:43:42,911
-He had some candy earlier.
-He couldn't wait until dinner?

1042
00:43:42,995 --> 00:43:44,955
Well, he's four.

1043
00:43:45,039 --> 00:43:47,749
-That's little.
-Four-year-olds in my village worked.

1044
00:43:47,833 --> 00:43:50,461
They made shoes, they
herded sheep, they hid guns.

1045
00:43:50,545 --> 00:43:52,588
ETHAN: Yom Kippur is scary.

1046
00:43:52,672 --> 00:43:55,048
I know, honey.
Go to your room, lock the door.

1047
00:43:55,132 --> 00:43:56,258
Yes, I would.

1048
00:43:56,342 --> 00:43:58,427
-Is that my toy?
-Not anymore.

1049
00:43:58,511 --> 00:44:01,472
SHIRLEY: Moishe, the flowers.
Have you seen the flowers?

1050
00:44:01,556 --> 00:44:04,266
My God, the flowers, they
almost don't seem real.

1051
00:44:04,350 --> 00:44:05,392
-ROSE: They're real.
-They don't look real.

1052
00:44:05,476 --> 00:44:06,727
-They are real.
-They don't look real.

1053
00:44:06,811 --> 00:44:07,895
-Well, they are.
-Are you sure?

1054
00:44:07,979 --> 00:44:09,354
-I'm sure.
-Excuse me.

1055
00:44:09,438 --> 00:44:10,898
Could I have your attention for a minute?

1056
00:44:10,982 --> 00:44:12,817
Stop touching the flowers, Shirley.

1057
00:44:12,901 --> 00:44:14,777
I have something I'd like to tell you.

1058
00:44:14,861 --> 00:44:17,030
All of you, on this special night.

1059
00:44:17,114 --> 00:44:19,574
You're a fucking child.

1060
00:44:19,658 --> 00:44:22,160
So this is a holy holiday
about atoning for our sins.

1061
00:44:22,244 --> 00:44:24,954
And lying, keeping things
from the ones you love,

1062
00:44:25,038 --> 00:44:27,123
-is a sin, and I have been…
-[ZELDA SPEAKS POLISH]

1063
00:44:27,207 --> 00:44:28,833
Ooh, lamb.

1064
00:44:28,917 --> 00:44:30,793
Is there something other than lamb?

1065
00:44:30,877 --> 00:44:32,170
Don't worry, Moishe, there's brisket.

1066
00:44:32,254 --> 00:44:33,922
Oh, I just hope she
made those little potatoes.

1067
00:44:34,006 --> 00:44:36,299
-I love those little potatoes.
-Um, Zelda, would you mind

1068
00:44:36,383 --> 00:44:37,800
holding off on the food for a minute?

1069
00:44:37,884 --> 00:44:38,801
-What?
-ABE: Why?

1070
00:44:38,885 --> 00:44:40,595
People are starving, Miriam.

1071
00:44:40,679 --> 00:44:42,139
-It's going to get cold.
-I promise this'll be quick.

1072
00:44:42,223 --> 00:44:45,434
-Give me the box back.
-[SPEAKS POLISH]

1073
00:44:45,518 --> 00:44:47,978
As I was saying, we
are family, and families

1074
00:44:48,062 --> 00:44:50,064
-should not lie to one another.
-Mm-hmm.

1075
00:44:50,148 --> 00:44:52,066
Especially about something that
could affect everybody someday.

1076
00:44:52,150 --> 00:44:54,068
This seems like it's gonna take a while.

1077
00:44:54,152 --> 00:44:55,611
I've got some pickles in my purse.

1078
00:44:55,695 --> 00:44:56,946
She is so resourceful, really.

1079
00:44:57,030 --> 00:44:58,656
I should carry pickles in my purse.

1080
00:44:58,740 --> 00:45:00,074
So, as I was saying,

1081
00:45:00,158 --> 00:45:02,409
a lot has happened in
my life over the last year,

1082
00:45:02,493 --> 00:45:04,233
and though I never
really planned it this way…

1083
00:45:04,317 --> 00:45:05,287
Who wants a kosher dill?

1084
00:45:05,371 --> 00:45:06,705
-Ooh, kosher dill.
-Over here, right over here.

1085
00:45:06,789 --> 00:45:08,290
ASTRID: I'll have a bite of Noah's.

1086
00:45:08,374 --> 00:45:10,251
-Have your own, Astrid.
-No, only if there's extra.

1087
00:45:10,335 --> 00:45:11,628
Astrid, take a fucking pickle.

1088
00:45:11,712 --> 00:45:14,923
This last year has been
very challenging for me.

1089
00:45:15,007 --> 00:45:18,635
And I found it leading
me in new directions.

1090
00:45:18,719 --> 00:45:20,971
Unexpected directions.

1091
00:45:21,055 --> 00:45:22,764
-Really unexpected.
-[SNORING]

1092
00:45:22,848 --> 00:45:24,224
ROSE: Shirley, you forgot your mother.

1093
00:45:24,308 --> 00:45:26,810
-Oh, I did. Oh, Moishe.
-I'm going, I'm going.

1094
00:45:26,894 --> 00:45:28,478
Um, anyhow. Uh, about my life.

1095
00:45:28,562 --> 00:45:30,188
-Pass the pickles.
-Papa.

1096
00:45:30,272 --> 00:45:31,856
Well, this is taking a very long time.

1097
00:45:31,940 --> 00:45:33,567
There we go. Right over here.

1098
00:45:33,651 --> 00:45:35,860
Zelda, you can bring the food now.

1099
00:45:35,944 --> 00:45:37,529
-Mama, I'm talking.
-Aren't you done?

1100
00:45:37,613 --> 00:45:39,823
I haven't started. Zelda, not yet.

1101
00:45:39,907 --> 00:45:42,618
Anyhow, so, this last year has
been very challenging for me,

1102
00:45:42,702 --> 00:45:43,911
-and…
-[DOORBELL RINGS]

1103
00:45:43,995 --> 00:45:47,540
[ZELDA SPEAKS POLISH]

1104
00:45:47,624 --> 00:45:50,042
Hi. I was, uh, summoned.

1105
00:45:50,126 --> 00:45:52,670
-Susie, come in.
-Uh, I think she's waiting

1106
00:45:52,754 --> 00:45:55,339
-for my papers or something.
-Uh, just get in here.

1107
00:45:55,423 --> 00:45:56,966
SHIRLEY: Okay, pass the pickles down.

1108
00:45:57,050 --> 00:46:00,387
MIDGE: Please, take a seat.

1109
00:46:03,473 --> 00:46:05,475
Mm. Comfortable chairs.

1110
00:46:06,935 --> 00:46:09,854
I invited Susie to be
here tonight with us,

1111
00:46:09,938 --> 00:46:12,399
to bear witness to
what I am about to say.

1112
00:46:12,483 --> 00:46:13,900
-What happened to Zelda?
-What?

1113
00:46:13,984 --> 00:46:15,944
Zelda. Usually answers the door.

1114
00:46:16,028 --> 00:46:18,280
How do you know what Zelda usually does?
Who are you?

1115
00:46:18,364 --> 00:46:20,907
-She's my friend.
-Yeah. Hi, Abe.

1116
00:46:20,991 --> 00:46:24,202
Very good.
Deducing that I am Abe, Miriam's father.

1117
00:46:24,286 --> 00:46:26,538
Hello, person I've never met before.

1118
00:46:26,622 --> 00:46:28,582
Nice to see you for the very first time.

1119
00:46:28,666 --> 00:46:32,252
Okay, so clearly I missed
a pretty hefty cocktail hour.

1120
00:46:32,336 --> 00:46:34,713
All right. Everyone, please just
let me say what I need to say.

1121
00:46:34,797 --> 00:46:37,758
-Not now, Zelda.
-[ZELDA SPEAKS POLISH]

1122
00:46:37,842 --> 00:46:39,843
I'm sure you've all
noticed that I've been acting

1123
00:46:39,927 --> 00:46:41,971
differently lately,
staying out at night a lot.

1124
00:46:42,055 --> 00:46:43,473
How would we know
you're staying out at night?

1125
00:46:43,557 --> 00:46:45,725
There is a reason for
this, and the reason is

1126
00:46:45,809 --> 00:46:49,104
I am pursuing a career
in stand-up comedy.

1127
00:46:52,441 --> 00:46:53,983
-You what?!
-ROSE: Abe.

1128
00:46:54,067 --> 00:46:55,860
ABE: This is outrageous.

1129
00:46:55,944 --> 00:46:57,654
How could you do this, Miriam?

1130
00:46:57,738 --> 00:47:00,281
What a secret to keep from your father.

1131
00:47:00,365 --> 00:47:02,075
Rose, did you know this?

1132
00:47:02,159 --> 00:47:03,451
-Of course I didn't know this.
-[DOORBELL RINGS]

1133
00:47:03,535 --> 00:47:05,411
-I don't understand.
-You don't understand?

1134
00:47:05,495 --> 00:47:07,664
What do you mean, a
career in stand-up comedy?

1135
00:47:07,748 --> 00:47:09,499
[DOOR OPENS]

1136
00:47:09,583 --> 00:47:11,919
Hello. I'm Rabbi Krinsky.

1137
00:47:12,003 --> 00:47:13,754
Come on in, Rabbi. Grab a seat.

1138
00:47:13,838 --> 00:47:16,799
-We're gonna be here a while.
<i>-Gut Yontiv,</i> Rabbi.

1139
00:47:16,883 --> 00:47:19,009
I've been working clubs all
over New York for months now.

1140
00:47:19,093 --> 00:47:20,427
I'm getting pretty good.

1141
00:47:20,511 --> 00:47:22,054
In fact, I have to leave early tonight,

1142
00:47:22,138 --> 00:47:24,556
because I've got a gig.
That's what we call it: a gig.

1143
00:47:24,640 --> 00:47:27,017
A booker is coming to
see me, and if I do well,

1144
00:47:27,101 --> 00:47:29,603
I'll get jobs in more clubs,
clubs outside of New York.

1145
00:47:29,687 --> 00:47:31,605
You were a plumber at Steiner's.

1146
00:47:31,689 --> 00:47:34,608
You came to fix our sink, and
when you left, it was worse.

1147
00:47:34,692 --> 00:47:36,985
-She's not a plumber, Mama.
-I should say not.

1148
00:47:37,069 --> 00:47:39,655
-That sink was not fixable.
-She's my manager.

1149
00:47:39,739 --> 00:47:41,198
-Her manager for what?
-For my stand-up.

1150
00:47:41,282 --> 00:47:43,243
-I can't believe you lied to us.
-SUSIE: I was under

1151
00:47:43,327 --> 00:47:44,869
the impression there
would be food at this thing.

1152
00:47:44,953 --> 00:47:47,080
I know it's a shock.
It was a shock to me, too,

1153
00:47:47,164 --> 00:47:48,623
but I've seen her
onstage, and she's good.

1154
00:47:48,707 --> 00:47:50,291
I think she could be really successful.

1155
00:47:50,375 --> 00:47:52,168
-As what?
-As a stand-up.

1156
00:47:52,252 --> 00:47:53,753
But how did you meet the plumber?

1157
00:47:53,837 --> 00:47:56,089
She's… Just try to stay with me.

1158
00:47:56,173 --> 00:47:58,007
-Who stays with the children?
-A lot of people.

1159
00:47:58,091 --> 00:47:59,718
Well, why haven't you ever called me?

1160
00:47:59,802 --> 00:48:02,011
Is this why you've been in
such a rotten mood lately?

1161
00:48:02,095 --> 00:48:03,263
What's wrong with me?

1162
00:48:03,347 --> 00:48:04,806
My mood has nothing to do with this.

1163
00:48:04,890 --> 00:48:06,516
I just found out about this.

1164
00:48:06,600 --> 00:48:08,518
My mood has been caused by something

1165
00:48:08,602 --> 00:48:10,603
and someone else entirely.

1166
00:48:10,687 --> 00:48:13,274
-I see. Meaning me.
-My mood has been turned rotten

1167
00:48:13,358 --> 00:48:16,444
by finding out my son
is a government spook.

1168
00:48:16,528 --> 00:48:18,738
A fed! A killer.

1169
00:48:18,822 --> 00:48:20,406
What are you talking about?

1170
00:48:20,490 --> 00:48:22,450
I'm talking about you being in the CIA.

1171
00:48:22,534 --> 00:48:24,076
Who told you?

1172
00:48:24,160 --> 00:48:26,454
That day at Bell Labs.
Do you think I'm an idiot?

1173
00:48:26,538 --> 00:48:28,831
And then Astrid sang like
a canary for your mother.

1174
00:48:28,915 --> 00:48:30,458
-You did?
-Oh, I don't know, maybe.

1175
00:48:30,542 --> 00:48:32,752
I had been fasting and I was weak and…
oh.

1176
00:48:32,836 --> 00:48:35,129
Why am I always starving?

1177
00:48:35,213 --> 00:48:36,672
Why is your manager a plumber?

1178
00:48:36,756 --> 00:48:38,507
I don't see how those
two skill sets interact.

1179
00:48:38,591 --> 00:48:40,217
Everyone, let's just calm down.

1180
00:48:40,301 --> 00:48:42,220
I… I didn't mean to start a whole thing.

1181
00:48:42,304 --> 00:48:44,055
This is not what I wanted.

1182
00:48:44,139 --> 00:48:46,266
Not everything in the
world is about you, Midge.

1183
00:48:46,350 --> 00:48:48,268
Except this, which is
literally all about me.

1184
00:48:48,352 --> 00:48:50,395
All right, let's put aside
the fact that your manager's

1185
00:48:50,479 --> 00:48:52,147
a plumber for a second.
Does Benjamin know?

1186
00:48:52,231 --> 00:48:54,024
-What?
-Who?

1187
00:48:54,108 --> 00:48:56,401
Benjamin? Who's Benjamin?
You never told me about a Benjamin.

1188
00:48:56,485 --> 00:48:58,361
Is this the guy you were
hanging out with in the Catskills?

1189
00:48:58,445 --> 00:48:59,181
Benjamin is not important.

1190
00:48:59,265 --> 00:49:00,572
I just want to know
how he feels about it.

1191
00:49:00,656 --> 00:49:02,199
Is it gonna affect your relationship?

1192
00:49:02,283 --> 00:49:04,868
-You have a relationship?
-SUSIE: This is not the best time

1193
00:49:04,952 --> 00:49:07,120
-to start a relationship.
-Yeah. You're just starting a career.

1194
00:49:07,204 --> 00:49:09,080
-We're gonna be touring.
-Touring. Yes.

1195
00:49:09,164 --> 00:49:10,957
You can't have a relationship
when you're touring.

1196
00:49:11,041 --> 00:49:12,794
Does Benjamin know
